[00:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Hey guys, Tyler here, technical artist with World Labs. Hope you\'re having a great day so far. Today, we\'re going to be going over how we get our environments from Marble into Unreal. Let\'s dive in. So, as you can see, we have a pipeline overview, and we\'re going to be going'

[00:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'over how we pull our environments from Marble into Unreal using the Vibe Mar plugin. So, our environments consist of three components. The environment itself will come in as a PLY or SPZ. Our collision mesh will come in as a'

[00:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'GLB, and we can get our skylight via a 360 pano that we will download as a PNG, and then we\'ll need to stop into Photoshop to convert to an HDR. If you don\'t have Photoshop, you can use any'

[00:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image editor of your choice as long as you can convert it save it out as a HDR, or you can use a free online uh image converter to convert the PNG to an HDR. Now that we have a high-level'

[00:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'understanding of the process, let\'s begin. So, we\'re going to step into Marble. As you can see, we have this amazing environment generated by a member of our community, and it looks absolutely amazing. And so, before we can grab the components, we just need to make sure a'

[01:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'few settings are configured correctly. So, if we we can come to the download button and click settings. We have a we have a few different settings. We have two key settings that we need to ensure are configured correctly.'

[01:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Splat file format and coordinate system. Now, our splat file format, we have two options, SPZ and PLY. The Vibe Mar plugin supports both uh SPZ and PLY. The main difference is that the SPZ is a'

[01:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more compressed file format resulting in a smaller file size. The PLY is just slightly bigger, but the smaller file size will result in quicker load times, so we recommend using the SPZ. Now, for the coordinate system,'

[01:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'uh OpenGL or OpenCV. OpenGL is a left-handed coordinate system, and this will work perfectly for applications like Unreal. OpenCV is a right-handed coordinate system. So, if we use that,'

[01:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the uh the the the environment will will come into Unreal upside down. So, we\'re going to choose OpenGL, and we\'re going to click save. Now that we\'ve configured our downloads, we can we can begin downloading our components. To do so, we\'re going to'

[02:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'click on the download icon, and we\'re going to click splats. This is going to download our environment. After that\'s done downloading, we can click on the download icon again and click collider mesh. This will give us our collision GLB.'

[02:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Next, we can go to more options and 360 pano, and this is going to download the skylight asset. Now that we\'ve done downloaded all the components for our environment, we can we can download the plugin. So, if you go to the link below,'

